{{Infobox rfam | Name = mir-598 | image = | width = | caption = | Symbol = mir-598 | AltSymbols = | Rfam = RF01059 | miRBase = | miRBase_family = MIPF0000393 | RNA_type = [[microRNA]] | Tax_domain = ''[[Eukaryote|Eukaryota]];'' | GO = | SO = | CAS_number = | EntrezGene = | HGNCid = | OMIM = | PDB = | RefSeq = | Chromosome = | Arm = | Band = | LocusSupplementaryData = }}
In molecular biology '''mir-598 microRNA''' is a short [[non-coding RNA|RNA]] molecule. [[MicroRNA]]s function to regulate the expression levels of other genes by several mechanisms.
==miR-598 in senescence== miR-598 has been shown to directly target and inhibit the [[Sir2]] homolog, silent information regulator one (SRT1) enzyme, in the [[senescence]] of human [[adipose tissue|adipose-tissue]]-derived [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s. Increased miR-598 expression during the senescent state is accompanied by a decreased expression of SRT1, meaning an absence of the inhibited [[p53]] [[acetylation]] usually observed with increased STR1 levels.<ref name="pmid22581440">{{cite journal|vauthors=Shin KK, Kim YJ, Hong CP, Yang JW, Bae YC, Jung JS | title=miR-598 induces replicative senescence in human adipose tissue-derived mesenchymal stem cells via silent information regulator 1. | journal=Mol Cell Biochem | year= 2012 | volume= 372| issue= 1-2| pages= 285| pmid=22581440 | doi=10.1007/s11010-012-1330-y | pmc= | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=22581440 }}</ref> miR-598 acts to modulate cellular senescence. More specifically, its overexpression induces senescence in early-passage cells whilst inhibition conversely sees a partial recovery of the ageing [[phenotype]] through increased [[cellular differentiation]].
