'''Robert Bentley Buckle''' (6 January 1802<ref>[http://genforum.genealogy.com/buckle/messages/247.html Genealogical web-site]</ref> &ndash; 16 September 1893<ref>'Obituary. Rev Canon R. Bentley Buckle', ''[[The Times]]'' (London, England), Wednesday, Sep 20, 1893; pg. 10; Issue 34061</ref>) was [[Archdeacon of Dorset]] <ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=35303 British History on-line]</ref> from 1836<ref>'THE CHURCH’ [[The Morning Post]]  (London, England), Friday, January 01, 1836; Issue 20302</ref> to 1862.<ref>'Ecclesiastical Intelligence', ''[[The Times]]'' (London, England), Friday, Oct 10, 1862; pg. 8; Issue 24373</ref>

Buckle was born on 6 January 1802, the fourth son of Edward Buckle of [[Sowerby, North Yorkshire|Sowerby]], Yorkshire. He was educated at [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]],<ref>'Cambridge University Senate', ''[[The Times]]'' (London, England), Tuesday, May 20, 1845; pg. 6; Issue 18928</ref> graduating BA as 4th [[Wrangler (University of Cambridge)|Wrangler]] in 1824.<ref>{{acad|id=BKL820RB|name=Buckle, Robert Bentley}}</ref> He was elected a [[Fellow]] of St John's in 1826.<ref>'The Ipswich Journal' (Ipswich, England), Saturday, April 29, 1826; Issue 4598</ref> He was [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|Rector]] of [[Moreton, Dorset]] until 1836; and then of [[Upwey, Dorset|Upwey in the same county]].<ref>[http://www.opcdorset.org/Broadwey-Upwey.Files/Upwey/1881Upwey.htm OPC]</ref> He was also a [[Prebendary]] of [[Salisbury Cathedral]].<ref>"Fasti Ecclesiae Anglicanae 1541-1857: volume 6: Salisbury diocese” Horn,J: London, 1986</ref>

