{{Politics of Switzerland}}
'''Two referendums''' were held in [[Switzerland]] in 1879.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & Stöver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', pp1902–1903 {{ISBN|9783832956097}}</ref> A federal law on subsidies for railways in the [[Alps]] was passed by 70.7% of voters on 19 January, whilst a referendum on the [[death penalty]] on 18 May was passed by 52.5% of voters and a majority of cantons.
==Background== The January referendum on rail subsidies was classed as an [[optional referendum]],<ref name=NS/> which meant that only a majority of the public vote was required for the proposals to be approved. The referendum on the death penalty involved amending article 65 of the federal constitution, and was a [[mandatory referendum]],<ref name=NS/> which required both a majority of voters and cantons to approve the proposals.<ref>Nohlen & Stöver, p1891</ref>
