{{EngvarB|date=June 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox person |name = Zeenat Begum |image = Zeenat-begum.jpg }}
'''Zeenat Begum''', credited as '''Zeenat''', was an [[Indian people|Indian]]/[[Pakistani people|Pakistani]] actress and Director.
==Music career== Zeenat Begum was a courtesan and a renowned classical singer. She was discovered by [[Amar Nath|Pandit Amar Nath]] circa 1937.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://anmolfankaar.com/specials/ek-fankaar/278-a-tribute-to-zeenat-begum-ji-the-singing-stalwart |title=Hamaare Mehmaan - Manohari Singh |publisher=Anmolfankaar.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403010108/http://anmolfankaar.com/specials/ek-fankaar/278-a-tribute-to-zeenat-begum-ji-the-singing-stalwart |archive-date=3 April 2015 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Her first success as a [[playback singer]] came in 1942 when she sang for Govind Ram's Punjabi film ''Mangti''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CKsEwcKeUgs |title=Zeenat Begum Male singer Nand Lal Noorpuri? Syed Dilawar Hussain? Mangti 1942 Ud ja bholya panchhia |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2015-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=clW7G-m-M_g&feature=related |title=Rehmat Bai (Rehmatbai) Mangti 1942 Din chadia te bankian naran punjabi old folk pakistani indian |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-01-07 |accessdate=2015-03-08}}</ref> The film was marked as first Golden Jubilee film produced in [[Lahore]]. Her first [[Hindi]] film was ''Nishani (1942)''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cineplot.com/music/zeenat-begums-song-list-1942-1951/ |title=Zeenat Begum’s Song List – (1942 – 1951) |publisher=Cineplot.com |date=2011-05-21 |accessdate=2015-03-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101132907/http://cineplot.com/music/zeenat-begums-song-list-1942-1951/ |archive-date=1 November 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She sang for other notable films including ''Panchhi (1944)'', ''[[Shalimar (1946 film)|Shalimar]]'' (1946), ''Shehar se Door'' (1946) and ''Daasi'' (1944).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cineplot.com/music/zeenat-begum/ |title=Zeenat Begum |publisher=Cineplot.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101141700/http://cineplot.com/music/zeenat-begum/ |archive-date=1 November 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
Zeenat Begum migrated from Lahore to [[Mumbai|Bombay]] in 1944. She sang for several music directors in Bombay, including Pandit Husan Lal Bhagat Ram, Ghulam Haidar, Pandit Gobind Ram etc. The last film she sang for in [[India]] was ''Mukhda (1951)''. She migrated to [[Pakistan]] and joined [[Lahore]] Radio station and worked there until the late 1950s.
She died on 12 November 1966 in [[Lahore]].<ref>[http://pakmag.dk/film/DoD/dod2.php?pid=437%20reg=6 ]{{dead link|date=March 2015}}</ref>
